## health-check.ts

### Catch block 1: `getActiveTokenForInstallation()` (lines 84-95)

```ts
// Line 83-95
let accessToken: string | null = null;
try {
  const tokenResult = await getActiveTokenForInstallation(
    installation,
    config,
    providerDef as ProviderDefinition
  );
  accessToken = tokenResult.token;
} catch {
  // If we can't get the token, we can't probe — treat as transient
  await recordTransientFailure(installation);
  return;
}
```

The catch clause at line 91 uses the bare `catch` keyword with no binding — the thrown error object is silently discarded. The block calls `recordTransientFailure(installation)` and returns early from the step.

### Catch block 2: `healthCheck.check()` (lines 101-111)

```ts
// Lines 101-111
try {
  status = await providerDef.healthCheck!.check(
    config as never,
    installation.externalId,
    accessToken
  );
} catch {
  // Network error / timeout — treat as transient failure
  await recordTransientFailure(installation);
  return;
}
```

Same pattern at line 107 — bare `catch` with no binding. Again delegates to `recordTransientFailure` and returns.

### How the logger is used elsewhere in this file

`log` is imported from `@vendor/observability/log/next` at line 18. It is called in five places outside those two catch blocks:

- Line 57: `log.info("[health-check] probing installations", { count })` — top of the probe loop
- Line 75: `log.warn("[health-check] provider not configured — skipping", { provider, installationId })` — inside the `!config` guard
- Line 123: `log.info("[health-check] healthy", { installationId, provider })` — after a healthy status response
- Line 131: `log.warn("[health-check] auth failure — firing lifecycle", { installationId, provider, status })` — before firing the lifecycle event
- Line 187: `log.warn("[health-check] transient failure recorded", { installationId, provider, newFailureCount, healthStatus })` — inside `recordTransientFailure()`

