## delivery-recovery.ts

### Catch block 1: `extractResourceId` inner try/catch (lines 77-85)

```ts
// Lines 77-85
let resourceId: string | null = null;
try {
  const providerDef = getProvider(providerName);
  if (providerDef && isWebhookProvider(providerDef)) {
    resourceId =
      providerDef.webhook.extractResourceId(parsedPayload) ?? null;
  }
} catch {
  // If extraction fails, proceed with null — ingest delivery handles it
}
```

Bare `catch` at line 83 with no binding and an empty body — the error is completely discarded. Execution falls through to the `preResolved` resolution block below.

### Catch block 2: Outer per-delivery catch (lines 138-140)

```ts
// Lines 138-140
} catch {
  failed.push(delivery.deliveryId);
}
```

Also a bare `catch` at line 138 with no binding. The only action is pushing `delivery.deliveryId` onto the `failed` array, which is returned in the summary object and logged at line 146-150 via `log.info("[delivery-recovery] complete", { replayed, skipped, failed })`.

### How the logger is used elsewhere in this file

`log` is imported from `@vendor/observability/log/next` at line 17. It appears in three places outside those catch blocks:

- Line 55: `log.info("[delivery-recovery] found stuck deliveries", { count: deliveries.length })` — after the DB fetch
- Lines 133-136: `log.error("[delivery-recovery] DB status update failed", { deliveryId, error: err })` — inside the DB status-reset try/catch, which notably does bind the error as `err` and passes it into the log call
- Line 146: `log.info("[delivery-recovery] complete", { replayed, skipped, failed })` — after the loop

The DB status-reset catch at lines 132-137 is the only catch block in either file that both binds the error (`catch (err)`) and passes it to the logger.

